Proximity: k nearest neighbor

In our study, two approaches of approximation were made: K nearest neighbor in terms of lag. County i was defined as a neighbor if it was connected within the k nearest neighbor of and j (\(/w_{ij}/\)=1; 0 otherwise). In our project, the kth nearest neighbor was considered as 1st 2nd and 4th nearest neighbor.

nc_shp <- sf:::as_Spatial(socal$geom)
soca_coords<-data.frame(gCentroid(nc_shp,byid=TRUE))
#1-NN
ca_kn1<-knn2nb(knearneigh(coordinates(nc_shp), k=1, RANN=FALSE))
plot(nc_shp, main="knn-1")
plot(ca_kn1, coordinates(nc_shp), add=TRUE,col="black")

#2-NN
ca_kn2<-knn2nb(knearneigh(coordinates(nc_shp), k=2, RANN=FALSE))
plot(nc_shp, main="knn-2")
plot(ca_kn2, coordinates(nc_shp), add=TRUE,col="black")

#4-NN
ca_kn4<-knn2nb(knearneigh(coordinates(nc_shp), k=4, RANN=FALSE))
plot(nc_shp, main="knn-4")
plot(ca_kn4, coordinates(nc_shp), add=TRUE,col="black")

Weights and the Adjacency Matrix: Row standardized

Weight plays an important role in examining spatial autocorrelation. Generally, the weights express as n*n matrix W among n observations. As shown below, each element "# in the W matrix is seen as spatial weights:

A caption

There are two ways of obtaining weight matrix: binary, and row standardized weight matrix. Binary defines weights 1 as neighboring features and 0 to all other features. While row standardized weight matrix takes given weights "# and divides them by the row sum: \(/w_{ij}(s)=\frac{w_{ij}}{\sum w_{ij}}\). This method ensures that all weights are between 0 and 1: \(/s=\sum_{i}\sum_{j} w_{ij}\), which makes the neighboring values better to interpret. Therefore, in this project. Row standardized was used in this project.

Model selection for predictor variables

Spatial Association-global

Morans I:

The results showed that there were significant spatial autocorrelations for both Median gross rent and Median house values using 1nn, 2nn, and 4nn row standardized weights. We noticed that for the same variable when we increased the knn number the Morans I statistics decreased so the magnitude of autocorrelation decreased. Giving the result, 1NN had better results indicating the strongest spatial autocorrelation.

A caption

Spatial Auto-Regressive Models

local Morans I

Both local and global Morans I test under the null hypothesis that there is no spatial autocorrelation for this variable. But different from the global Morans I that calculates the overall spatial relationships, local Morans I calculates for each unit of location.

From the local Morans I plots we can see that similar patterns for 1NN and 2NN. Counties in western California for the median gross rent. Blue dots indicating there was significant spatial autocorrelation among those counties. As we can see that when the number of KNN increased from 1NN to 2NN, the number of blue dots in the same area increased. For 4NN, there was one more clustering effect located in southern California.

For the median house value, we can see similar patterns that high values were clustered in western California. Also, 1NN and 2NN show that the median house value in southern California has a distinct clustering effect. When the number of knn increased, the number of clustered counties were increased as well.

#1. Local Moran's I for the median gross rent
moranLocmgr1<-localmoran(socal$median.gross.rent,ca_kn1_ww, p.adjust.method="bonferroni")

Autoregressive Models:

Simultaneous Autoregressive Models (SAR)

Median gross rent: For people with the same median age, there was a positive relationship between median gross rent and rent between 20-30% income. For people with the same median age, there was a positive relationship between median gross rent and rent between 40-50% income After adding race, the regression estimates were not significant and had a higher AIC. Therefore, the race variable was removed from the model. The parameter of spatial association \(\rho\) was 0.56537.

mod_sarlag = lagsarlm(median.gross.rent~Age+rentpctless10+rent1020+rent2030+rent3040+rent4050, data = socal,listw=ca_kn2_ww, zero.policy=T, tol.solve=1.0e-12)
summary(mod_sarlag)

Median house value: For people with the same median age, there was a positive relationship between median gross rent and rent between 20-30% income. After adding race, the regression estimates were not significant and had a higher AIC. Therefore, the race variable was removed from the model. The parameter of spatial association \(\rho\) was 0.75601.

Conditional Autoregressive Models (CAR)

Median gross rent: For people with the same median age, there was a positive relationship between median gross rent and rent between 10- 20%. For people with the same median age, there was a positive relationship between median gross rent 20-30%. For people with the same median age, there was a positive relationship between median gross rent 30-40%. For people with the same median age, there was a positive relationship between median gross rent rent between 40-50% income. After adding race, the regression function was not significant and had a higher AIC. Therefore, race was removed from the model. Lambda: 0.6182.

Conclusion

In this project, we used KNN nearest neighbor to investigate the spatial autocorrelation for median rent and median house value variables and we found statistically significant clustering in the bay area. When we used 4NN, southern California was also found significant clustering effects. spatial autoregressive models to investigate the association between age, race, median rent, rent as a percentage of income separately for the median rent and median house value. After comparing the results of the SAR model and CAR model,the SAR provided a better prediction for median gross rent, and the CAR model provided a better prediction for the median house value.
